<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>A Seven Step Recovery Program -- PFF
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul>
<blockquote>
<a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<br>
<h2>A Seven Step Recovery Program</h2>
<P>
by <a href="/pff/people/director.html#Huffington">Arianna Huffington</a>
<P>
The GOP has had a string of bad news recently: For the first time
since 1962, a Democrat was elected to the Senate from Oregon;
in a recent ABC/Washington Post poll, 74% disagreed with how the
Republican Congress is handling the economy (versus 50% disagreeing
with Clinton's performance); the GOP has been completely outmaneuvered
by Clinton on the balanced budget and has even retreated on its
promise not to raise the debt ceiling.
<P>
There are two ways for the GOP to deal with all these setbacks.
One: They can spin them. Two: They can heed them as the wake-up
call they are. So far they've chosen the spin cycle. They're comforting
themselves with transparent excuses: The defeat in Oregon was
too narrow to be significant; Oregon was one of only three states
to elect a new Democratic governor in 1994; Oregon voted for Dukakis
in 1988; it's the Senate with wimpy Republicans caving in; it's
the uncompromising House freshmen, recalcitrant and extremist;
it's Clinton, the Great Empathizer; it's Dick Morris, the brilliant
strategist.
<P>
As anyone familiar with 12-step programs can tell you, there is
nothing as inventive as the human mind in denial. And since the
GOP is unquestionably in denial, here is my suggested seven step
recovery program. (In the budget saving spirit of the times, we
have reduced 12 steps to 7.)
<P>
The first step for the GOP is to acknowledge that it has a problem.
<P>
The second step is to stop whining, especially about the media.
As some sage once said, the Constitution guarantees a free press
-- it does not guarantee a fair press. The GOP should forget about
whether the media is misrepresenting their message and go about
improving it.
<P>
The third step is to stop sounding like accountants and to begin
sounding like leaders. The good news for Republicans is that 80
percent of the American public wants a balanced budget. The bad
news for them is that so does Bill Clinton -- in seven years with
CBO numbers. So Republicans need to move the debate beyond balancing
the budget, not because this battle is over, but because, for
the moment, the President has framed the debate in way that makes
it impossible for Republicans to win. Both sides want to balance
the budget, but the President, in his own words, wants to &quot;balance
the budget in a way that reflects our values.&quot;
<P>
The fourth step is for the GOP to stop repeating, ad nauseum,
that it is not cutting anything -- but merely reducing the rate
of growth. This may be factually correct, but didn't Republicans
campaign on the theme of cutting things -- cutting government,
cutting entitlements, cutting taxes? Did they come to power to
reduce the rate of growth of government or did they came to power
to reduce government?
<P>
So instead of being so defensive about what they are doing, I
suggest that they take step five and be courageous enough to tell
the American people just what they want to do: reverse 60 years
of New Deal and Great Society thinking, according to which all
solutions to social and economic problems revolve around government.
Yes, this is bold, but a time of crisis requires boldness, decisiveness,
and honesty. This rethinking of the role of government has to
go hand in hand with a fundamental redefinition of the role of
the citizen -- challenging the American people to meet less from
Washington with more from themselves and their communities.
<P>
The sixth step, without which the revolution will remain stalled,
is to talk about community solutions -- about what is working
around America. They must talk about it not once in a while but
as frequently and as seriously as they have been talking about
balancing the budget. The GOP must go beyond just talking about
dismantling government, and start talking about what they are
going to replace it with. This is a critical step. When Newt Gingrich
first became Speaker, he was going to hold Congressional &quot;success
hearings.&quot; He was going to bring to the Capitol the community
leaders who are making things work and are turning lives around
-- introducing them to the American public as the people who embody
the alternative vision of rebuilding America.
<P>
The final step is to bring a sense of urgency to the debate --
to shift it from balancing the books in seven years to taking
steps right now to reform conditions in education, in welfare,
in the ways we deal with those most in need among us. Let Dick
Gephardt and David Bonior defend a broken system of government
programs that has left millions of children hungry, abused or
neglected, and let the Republicans speak of weaving a real safety
net from the involvement and resources -- in time and money --
of millions of Americans.
<P>
Instead of spinning all these setbacks or blaming the media, it
is time the GOP took these seven simple steps to produce a message
that has both economic and moral truth on its side. If Republicans
truly want to recover from what ails them, they must seize the
moral high ground without which no party can be a majority party.
<P>
<I>Arianna Huffington is a senior fellow at the Progress and Freedom
Foundation, where she chairs the Center for Effective Compassion
</I>

<P><br>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
