<HEAD>

<title>  Key Issues Before the Telecom Conferees
 -- PFF</title>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="Mike Manning">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>Key Issues Before the Telecom Conferees</h2>
<b>Progress On Point</b>
<br>Periodic Commentaries on the Policy Debate
<P>
<i>Release 1.7, December 7, 1995                                        
                   </i>
<P>
By <a href="/pff/people/sfellow.html#Myers">William C. Myers</a>
<P><br>

 There are four key issues pending with telecommunications conferees:
<ol>
<li><a href="#net">Internet Regulation</a>
<li><a href="#puhca">PUHCA</a>
<li><a href="#reg">Price Regulation</a>
<li><a href="#comp">Long Distance Competition</a></ol>
<P>

<P><a name="net"></a>
<center><B>INTERNET REGULATION</B>
<P></center>
Earlier this year, the House voted 420 to 4 in support of the
&quot;Cox-Wyden-White&quot; approach to Internet regulation and
&quot;cyberporn.&quot; This approach established no new criminal
penalties for pornography on the Net; provided immunity for on-line
service providers who enable users to block or screen access to
objectionable material; and, prohibited the FCC from regulating
the Net.  The Senate approved the more intrusive &quot;Exon&quot;
approach, which Speaker Gingrich opposed.
<P>
<i>This morning, House conferees met to decide what approach to
Internet regulation they would advance in Conference</i>.  They
adopted the White approach, which maintains most Cox-Wyden provisions
but also includes new criminal penalties for transmission of pornographic
material on the Net.  In adopting the White approach, however,
they changed the standard for application of these penalties from
the limited Constitutional standard of &quot;material harmful
to minors&quot; to &quot;indecency&quot; -- a killer amendment
in the eyes of the broad Internet, on-line provider and freedom
coalition (e.g., Americans for Tax Reform; Citizens for a Sound
Economy, Heritage Foundation).  The vote among House members was
17-16, with Republicans Goodlatte, Gallegly, Hoke, Moorhead, Frisa,
Barton, Hyde, Schaefer, Buyer, Flanigan, Barr, Paxon and Stearns
voting for the &quot;indecency&quot; approach.  The Christian
Coalition was strongly supportive of this change, with the freedom
coalition strongly opposed.  Democrats who supported the &quot;indecency&quot;
standard included Conyers, Schroeder, Gordon and Jackson-Lee.
<P>
<i>If this provision cannot be changed back to the original White
approach, many of those who supported the White approach will
work to kill the bill</i>.
<P><a name="puhca"></a>
<center><B>PUHCA</B>
<P></center>
The Senate telecommunications bill would allow the 14 registered
utility holding companies under the Public Utility Holding Company
Act of 1935 (PUHCA) to enter telecommunications and related businesses
on the same basis as other companies (utility and non-utility).
 <i>Earlier this year, Speaker Gingrich called for such flexibility</i>
(see attached news release).  
<P>
The House bill has no provision comparable to the Senate language.
 In staff conference negotiations so far, the House has refused
to accept the Senate PUHCA language based on the assertion, advanced
most often by Congressmen Dingell and Markey, that it has insufficient
consumer protections for captive utility ratepayers.  (In reality,
the Senate bill contains extensive consumer protections aimed
at ensuring that captive ratepayers do not subsidize telecommunications
activities.)
<P>
<i>Senate staff have now offered additional consumer protections
in an attempt to break the impasse; no response has yet come from
the House</i>.
<P><a name="reg"></a>
<center><B>PRICE REGULATION</B>
<P></center>
Staff of House and Senate conferees have agreed to strike language
contained in both versions of the legislation requiring the FCC
and state public service commissions to replace old-style, cost-plus
rate-of-return regulation with price regulation.  This requirement
was included on the grounds that price regulation would not only
streamline Federal and state telecommunications regulation, but
would also reduce any financial incentives that the local telephone
companies might have to cross subsidize competitive services with
revenues earned from non-competitive offerings.
<P>
Price regulation requirements were included largely through the
efforts of Senator Lott and Congressman Tauzin.  <i>Staff apparently
decided to strike the provisions from the conference report in
deference to pressure from the White House and some state regulatory
commissions who view the requirement as an encroachment on their
jurisdiction</i>.
<P>
The move from rate of return regulation to price regulation was
a key feature of both bills, supported especially by Sen. Pressler
and Cong. Fields, and <i>its elimination from the final bill would
make it significantly less pro-competitive</i>.
<P><a name="comp"></a>
<center><B>LONG DISTANCE COMPETITION</B>
<P></center>
During the telecom debate in September, the House expressly rejected
provisions that would have delayed Bell company entry into the
long distance market until they were able to demonstrate that
local phone markets were competitive (i.e., a facilities based
test).  The House rejected this proposal out of concern it would
create a disincentive for long distance carriers to enter local
phone markets with the Bells, thereby delaying Bell entry into
the long distance market.
<P>
<i>Though the Senate staff apparently has agreed to the provisions
in the House bill, the long distance carriers have persuaded Chairman
Bliley and Rep. Fields to reconsider the type of facilities-based
local competition test that the House earlier rejected</i>. Neither
the House conferees nor the conference committee as a whole have
voted on this issue. 
<P><hr width="50%"><P>
<I>William C. Myers is vice president for policy and a senior
fellow at The Progress &amp; Freedom Foundation. The views expressed
are solely those of the author.</I>
<P><P><center>



</center></blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
