<HEAD>
<title>Infotainment:  Tom Jefferson and te ACLU</title>
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">

<center><h2>Tom Jefferson and the ACLU</h2>
by <a href="#bio">Jessica Shaver</a>
<P>
Courtesy of <i>the Forum</i>
<hr><P>
<i>What would have happened if the Founding Fathers had tried to
draft the Declaration of Independence today with a lawyer from
the American Civil Liberties Union on the committee....</i>
<hr width="50%">
</center><P>
JOHN ADAMS: Gentlemen, let us pray that the Almighty will grant
us wisdom in the wording of this document and in setting the course
for this new nation.
<P>
ACLU: I object! God has no place in government!
<P>
BENJAMIN FRANKLIN: Sir, to forbid the rightful acknowledgment
of God in the affairs of state would be an abridgment of the religious
freedom we came to this country to enjoy.
<P>
THOMAS JEFFERSON: Religion is the foundation of all just government.
Our laws have their source and their authority in the Bible. Don't
we need wisdom and His blessing? The Bible says, &quot;The fear
of the Lord is the beginning of wisdom&quot; and &quot;Blessed
is the nation whose God is the Lord.&quot;
<P>
ACLU: Don't forget that it was abuses by a state religion that
were partly responsible for bringing us to this point of separation
from England.
<P>
JEFFERSON: We need separation of church and state to prevent the
church from controlling the state, or the state the church--not
to prevent the church from civilizing the state and holding it
morally accountable.
<P>
ACLU: You are imposing your belief in God on me! I'm an atheist!
<P>
ADAMS: Whether you are an atheist or not does not affect God's
existence. Oh, very well. Those who wish to may privately and
individually acknowledge God's ruling in our lives.
<P>
Now, Mr. Jefferson will read us the Declaration of Independence,
subject to our revisions.
<P>
JEFFERSON: 'We hold these truths to be self-evident, that all
men are created equal--'
<P>
ACLU: Objection! 'Truths' is a relative term. What's true for
you may not be true for me. And creation is a religious concept.
<P>
ADAMS: Then let us amend that statement to read, 'We hold these
opinions to be self-evident, to some, that all men are equal--'
<P>
ACLU: Sexist!
<P>
ADAMS: How about 'all persons are equal'?
<P>
ACLU: Better. But I'd prefer, 'all races, genders and lifestyles
are Equal--'
<P>
FRANKLIN: 'lifestyles'? What are lifestyles'?
<P>
ACLU: Sexual preference: adultery, homosexuality, prostitution,
pedophilia--
<P>
FRANKLIN: I pray our nation never--
<P>
ACLU; If you people persist in your references to prayer, I'll
seek a court injunction.
<P>
ADAMS: Order! Order! Gentlemen! Mr. Jefferson, please continue!
<P>
JEFFERSON: '--That all lifestyles, etc., are equal and that all
persons find themselves possessing certain arguably inalienable
rights, that among these are life--'
<P>
ACLU: Objection! Infringes on a woman's right to reproductive
choice.
<P>
JEFFERSON: '. . . liberty and the pursuit of happiness'
<P>
FRANKLIN: This doesn't even make sense! How can people have 'rights'
which are not granted by anyone? How can those who do not have
a right to life profit from their rights to liberty and the pursuit
of happiness?
<P>
I move we kick this lawyer out of the meeting!
<P>
ACLU: Objection! Violation of the first amendment to the Constitution:
my right to free speech.
<P>
ADAMS: What is the Constitution?
<P>
ACLU: Freedom of speech extends not only to political dissidents,
such as ourselves, but to moral relativists, and to those who
may in the future seek to destroy what we are now building.
<P>
FRANKLIN: God forbid!
<P>
ACLU: Freedom of religion means that moral values can have no
influence on public life.
<P>
ADAMS: But that is nonsense! This would mean that our public prayers
would violate the laws of the nation we are in the process of
creating.
<P>
ACLU: That's what the Supreme Court will say!
<P>
FRANKLIN: If that's how you people are going to interpret it,
I hope to God we never do draft it.
<P>
ADAMS: Gentlemen, we seem to be deadlocked. Every attempt on the
part of men of good will to establish this nation seems to be
actively thwarted by the lawyer from the ACLU. The revolution
is hereby cancelled. <P>
<P>
<a name="bio"></a>
<i>Jessica Shaver is the author of "Gianna:  Aborted... And Lived to Tell About It" a contributing editor for </I>Virtue<i> magazine and </i>The Christian Communicator<i> and is a freelance writer for such publications as </i>The Los Angeles Times, Focus on the Family, Moody Magazine, Family Circle,<i> and </i>Christianity Today.  <i> Ms. Shaver has a Bachelor of Theology and a Master's in English Literature</i>.<P><P>

