<HEAD>

<title>  Power to the People -- PFF</title>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Mike Manning">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right" border="0"></a>
<h2><I>Power to the People</h2></I>
<b>Progress On Point</b>
<br>Periodic Commentaries on the Policy Debate
<P>
<i>Release 1.4 Nov 95                                        
                   </i>
<P>
by <a href="/pff/people/sfellow.html#Block">Michael Block</a> and Hon. John Shadegg</
<P><p><P></center>
 Over the past several years there has been a dramatic retrenchment
of government's economic role.  Around the globe various countries
have privatized their banks, steel mills, post offices, air traffic
control systems and roads.  The change has been no less dramatic
in the energy sector.  Great Britain and Chile have already privatized
their electricity industries and several other countries are now
following suit.  Given this return to private enterprise in former
bastions of statism, it is somewhat embarrassing that, while the
Russians have privatized more than 10,000 firms in the past couple
of years, the U.S. Congress is finding it impossible to privatize
four agencies that generate and distribute electricity in the
South and West, and at most represent one-twentieth of one percent
of our GDP.
<P>

 These agencies, the Power Marketing Administrations (or PMAs
to their fans), were created over the past sixty years to market
power generated at dams operated by the Corps of Engineers and
the Bureau of Reclamation.  The electricity generated at these
facilities is sold at mostly below market rates to rural electric
co-operatives and local government utilities -- a group commonly
called &quot;preference customers&quot;.  
<P>
 Privatization of the PMAs has foundered on the effect it would
have on the electricity rates charged to consumers of this low-cost
power.  So far, various proposals to address this problem have
been lacking.  The preference customers have advocated that the
PMAs be sold to them at bargain prices.  This has run into the
opposition of private utility companies that also want the chance
to bid on the assets.  The House Resources Committee's plan, now
defunct, would have sold the Southeastern Power Administration
(SEPA) to the highest bidder, and mitigated any &quot;rate shock&quot;
with a regulatory rate cap.  
<P>
 The sale of SEPA has been waylaid by traditional interest group
politics.  The beneficiaries of this program (i.e., the preference
customers who receive subsidized power) have a concentrated interest
in this issue that, as usual, has trumped the general interest
of taxpayers who paid for the construction and operation of the
PMAs and currently subsidize the power.  It's been reported that
even the Bass Anglers Sporting Society fought the sale.  It seems
they fear the owners of the privatized dams will increase fees
at bass rich reservoirs.  This is yet another example of how good
intentions are simply not enough to move the process in Washington.
<P>
 In order to privatize the PMAs and, more  generally, in order
to truly reform the Federal government, we are going to have to
do more than just think good thoughts and exhort Congress to vote
the general interest.  We have to make change something special
interests desire rather than fear.
<P>
 In the area of privatization, we should learn from the experiences
of other countries around the world.  Through voucher and other
plans foreign governments have transformed natural opponents of
privatization such as employees and customers into stakeholders
and advocates.  The Czech Republic's voucher scheme was extraordinarily
successful.  It made the benefits of privatization obvious even
to &quot;widows and orphans&quot; for whom terms like &quot;shares&quot;
or &quot;stock exchange&quot; had still been rather foggy.
<P>
 Taking inspiration from the Czech experience we need to privatize
the PMAs in way that turns potential opponents into proponents.
 The way to do this is to convert the PMAs into government corporations.
 Next, the final consumers of PMA power -- those who use power
bought from a PMA to light their homes or run their businesses
-- would be given the option to purchase stock in the PMAs at
a price reflecting the value of the PMAs under current operating
conditions.  This option would be fully transferrable and so consumers
could either exercise it, thus become part-owners of the corporation,
or sell it to whomever they want under any conditions they agree
upon.  
<P>
  Unlike the proposals put forward so far by the preferred customers,
this legislation will open the sale up to any qualified bidder.
 This will ensure that the assets will wind up with those who
can use them most efficiently.  This approach will move decisions
about ownership and operation of these facilities out of committee
rooms in Washington and give those decisions to people who have
a direct interest in the outcome.  Interested buyers will have
to woo consumers instead of sending lobbyists to Washington. 
<P>
 However, unlike open sale proposals put forward so far by private
utilities, it will not leave in place an interest group protected
only by a governmental regulatory structure.  A wide-open bidding
process will bid up the value of the PMAs giving consumers the
chance to realize substantial gains by selling their options.
 Consumers will be compensated for any possible &quot;rate shock&quot;
through cash from the sale of their option, or appreciated stock.
<P>
 Most importantly, it will convert those who are now most fearful
of any change in ownership of the PMAs into supporters of privatization.
 Consumers will take an active interest in the process as they
check the financial pages of their newspaper every day for the
latest offer.  They will write their Congressman asking not to
stop the sale, but to expedite it so they can realize their gain
from the sale on the open market.
<P>
 In December of 1986, on the day Margaret Thatcher's government
was launching its privatization of British Gas, a crowd of about
a hundred people gathered in the foyer of the Manchester Stock
Exchange.  Before the sale, the government had done everything
possible--staggered payments, bonus and voucher schemes, and free
and matching shares--to encourage and empower former customers
and employees to buy shares.  That day, the foyer soon took on
the atmosphere of a bookie's office.  As the price of the newly
floated shares rose, the crowd cheered.  When prices faltered,
they booed.  This shows how a creative plan can capture the imagination
and support of the public.  
<P>
 The approach described above can change the current political
dynamic in a similar and dramatic way.  It would end government
involvement in generating electricity, an area where it no longer
needs to be involved.  It will also provide an example of the
innovative types of solutions that can be used to restructure
other areas of the Federal government.
<P>
 This concept will be incorporated into a bill that will be introduced
by one of the authors, Congressman Shadegg.  The plan will avoid
a sale to the current preference customers at below market rates,
which would not truly privatize these facilities.  A preference
sale would merely move the facilities from the left hand of the
government to the right, perpetuate subsidized power and hurt
the taxpayer.  
<P>
 The privatization plan embodied in the bill also avoids a &quot;trust
us&quot; sale to the existing private power companies under terms
which ask the current customers give up their benefit for nothing
and rely on a government regulatory structure to protect them
from rate shock.
<P>
 Following the example used around the world, giving a fully transferable
purchase option to the current customers meets two important criteria.
 First, it will achieve privatization at market rates, and second,
it will fully compensate the current customers.
<P>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</HTML>
