<html>
<head>
<title>Senior Fellows -- PFF</title>
</head>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="../notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454" ALINK="#FF0000">
<blockquote><ul>
<a href="/pff"><img src="../pffdoc.gif" border="0" align="right"></a>
<map name="people">
<area shape="rect" coords="0,0,70,20" href="mission.inc"> 
<area shape="rect" coords="71,0,144,20" href="director.html"> 
<area shape="rect" coords="145,0,249,20" href="sfellow.html"> 
<area shape="rect" coords="251,0,364,20" href="afellow.html"> 
<area shape="rect" coords="365,0,415,20" href="staff.html"> 
<area shape="rect" coords="417,0,459,20" href="/pff"> 
</map>

<center><a href="people.map"><img src="i-people.gif" border="0" align="top" ISMAP USEMAP="#people"></a>
<h1>Senior Fellows</h1></center>
<p>

<dt><a href="/pff/multi/people/block.jpg"><img hspace="8" alt="Picture of Block" src="/pff/multi/people/block.gif"></a> <b><a name="Block">Michael K. Block</a></b>
<P>
<ul>Dr. Michael Block serves the Foundation as a Senior Fellow on the "Competition in Electric Power" project.  The project is designing a replacement model for the current bureaucratic and costly regulatory system in the electric utility industry that will result in a truly competitive electricity market.  Block is a professor of economics and a professor of law at the university of Arizona.  In addition, he is chairman of the Arizona Constitutional Defense Council and is president of the Goldwater Institute for Public Policy in Pheonix, Arizona.  Block received his Ph.D. in Economics from <a href="http://www.stanford.edu">Stanford University</a> in 1972, where he previously received his B.A. and M.A., both in economics.</ul>
<P>
<dt><a href="/pff/multi/people/fortson.jpg"><img hspace="8" alt="Picture of Jane Fortson" src="/pff/multi/people/fortson.gif"></a> <b><a name="Fortson">Jane Fortson</a></b>

<ul>Forston comes to the Foundation with an extensive background in
finance and urban development. A Managing Director at Lewis, deRozario Inc., she
served as senior investment banker to numerous municipal and mortgage related
clients underwriting in excess of $2 billion in securities. Fortson was appointed
by former Mayor Andrew Young as commissioner of the <a href="http://www.city.net/countries/united_states/georgia/atlanta/">Atlanta</a> Housing Authority.
She is a founding Director of the Atlanta Neighborhood Development Partnership
and served in the founding Secretariat for the <a href="http://www.emory.edu/CARTER_CENTER/homepage.html">Carter Centers</a>
initiative, the Atlanta Project.</ul>

<p>
<a name="Higgins"</a>
<dt><a href="/pff/multi/people/higgins.jpg"><img hspace="8" alt="Picture of Higgins" src="/pff/multi/people/higgins.gif"></a>
<b>Heather Higgins</a></b>
<ul>Higgins is the executive
director of the Council on Culture & Community, which
examines and promotes attitudes and values at the core
of democratic capitalism and American civilization.
Previously, Higgins worked on Wall Street, serving
most recently as portfolio manager and vice president
for U.S. Trust.  She has been an editorial writer
for <a href="http://www.wsj.com"><i>The Wall Street Journal,</i></a> assistant editor
at <i>The Public Interest</i> and a political commentator for
<a href="gopher://info.umd.edu:925/">CNN</a> 
and 
<a href="http://www.pbs.org">PBS.</a></ul>
<p>
<a name="Lenard">
<dt><a href="/pff/multi/people/lenard.jpg"><img hspace="8" alt="Picture of Thomas Lenard" src="/pff/multi/people/lenard.gif"></a> <b><a name="Lenard">Thomas Lenard</a></b>
</a>
<ul>Senior fellow and director of
regulatory studies, Thomas Lenard joined the Foundation
after seven years with the microeconomic consulting firm
of Heiden Associates, where he specialized in regulatory and
antitrust economics.  In the mid-1980s he was a special advisor for
economic policy at the White House Office of Management and
Budget.  Lenard also was a senior economist for the
Council on Wage and Price Stability.  He earned his
bachelor of arts degree in 
<a href="gopher://gopher.econ.wisc.edu/">economics</a>
from the 
<a href="http://www.wisc.edu/">University of Wisconsin</a>
in 1966, and his doctorate degree in
economics from 
<a href="http://www.brown.edu">Brown University</a>
in 1972.</ul>

<p>

<dt><a href="/pff/multi/people/myers.jpg"><img hspace="8" alt="Picture of William Myers" src="/pff/multi/people/myers.gif"></a> <b><a name="Myers">William C. Myers</a></b>

<ul>




l.</ul>
The Foundation's policy team -- staff, senior fellows, adjunct fellows and fellow travelers -- works to provide the political philosophy and public policies which will inform the civic discussion which is creating the next generation of American society and government.  The Foundation's Vice President for Policy, Bill Myers, guides that work (when tolerated), collaborates on it (when permitted), cajoles (often), harasses (sometimes),  and, in other ways, shepherds PFFs policy efforts.  So far, that work aims to assess The Big Change, divine The New Majority, replace the FCC, transcend the FDA, free public utilities, foster home ownership, and otherwise build a positive, practical vision for America.  When not so engaged, Myers threatens to play the part of Senior Fellow in order to write and speak on subsidiarity, federalism and public policies which are best addressed locally, topics on which he once frequently published.  Myers has previously provided more traditional direction to the policy activities of the Free Congress Foundation, the American Legislative Exchange, the State Policy Network, and the South Carolina Policy Council

<p>

<dt><a href="/pff/multi/people/olasky.jpg"><img hspace="8" alt="Picture of Marvin Olasky" src="/pff/multi/people/olasky.gif"></a> <b><a name="Olasky">Marvin Olasky</a></b>

<ul>A senior fellow at the Foundation, Olasky is studying the most
effective methods for assisting the truly needy in society and designing
replacements for the current welfare state. He is the author of The Tragedy of
American Compassion, hailed as a landmark work in the study of charity. He is
writing its sequel, The Promise of American Compassion, while at the Foundation.
Olasky is also editor of World, a Christian weekly news magazine, and has written
numerous articles for publications such as <a href="/nationalreview/welcome.html">National Review</a> and <a href="/heritage/p_review/">Policy Review</a>.</ul>

<p>

<dt><a href="/pff/multi/people/sullivan.gif"><img src="/pff/multi/people/sull-sm.gif" alt="Louis Sullivan" hspace="8"></a><b><a name="Sullivan">Louis W. Sullivan, M.D.</a></b>
<p>
<ul>
The Honorable Louis M. Sullivan, M.D. chairs the Foundation's Medical Innovation Project.  After serving as Secretary of the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services in the Bush Administration, the longest tenure (47 months) of any HHS Secretary in U.S. History, Dr. Sullivan returned to Morehouse School of Medicine (MSM).  As Head of HHS, Dr. Sullivan oversaw the Federal agency responsible for the major health, welfare, food and drug safety, medical research and income security programs in service of the American people.<p>

Dr. Sullivan became the founding Dean and director of the Medical Education Program at Morehouse College in 1975, the first minority medical school founded in the United States in this century.  In 1978, MSM began operation as a two year program in the basic medical sciences, admitting its first class of 24 students.  On July 1, 1981, the Morehouse School of Medicine became independent from Morehouse College with Dr. Sullivan as its Dean and first President, and on July 1, 1983, MSM became a member of the Atlanta University Center.<p>


<dt><a href="/pff/multi/people/vlahos.jpg"><img hspace="8" alt="Picture of Michael Vlahos" src="/pff/multi/people/vlahos.gif"></a> <b><a name="Vlahos">Michael Vlahos</a></b>

<ul>While our lives move inevitably from future to past, Vlahos, a
senior fellow at the Foundation, has tried to march in a different direction.
From Bronze Age archaeology, Byzantium, and British imperial history at <a href="http://www.cis.yale.edu/FrontDoor/">Yale
University</a>, he moved to foreign relations and modern war at the <a href="http://www.tufts.edu/departments/fletcher/fletchCatalog.html">Fletcher School
of Law & Diplomacy</a>. As Director of Security Studies at <a href="http://www.jhu.edu/">Johns Hopkins</a>-SAIS, he
widened his view to take on war and society. So broadened, he was asked to turn
the <a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/White_House/Cabinet/html/Department_of_State.html">State Departments</a> Center for the Study of Foreign Affairs into a real,
long-range think tank. He did. Its theme became -- and, in 1988, just in time --
world change. Vlahos was then commissioned to help turn the U.S. Navys
rangefinders toward Big Change, while at the Center for Naval Analyses. In the
Foundation, he has found a place that not only sees the ongoing transformation of
American life -- the Big Change -- but that actively seeks to be a part of it.
Now Vlahos writes, in print and in the ether, about where we are going and how we
will get there.</ul>

<p>

<dt><a href="/pff/multi/people/weber.gif"><img hspace="8" alt="Picture of Vin Weber" src="/pff/multi/people/weber-sm.gif"></a> <b><a name="Weber">Vin Weber</a></b>

<ul>Former six-term Congressman Vin Weber
leads the Foundation's new <a href="/pff/political_renewal.html">Center for Political Renewal</a>.  His
activities will include examining the nature of the next majority
coalition in American politics.  Weber spent the past two years as
a leader of <a href="/empower/">Empower America</a>, a conservative grassroots advocacy
organization.  He also is a political commentator on 
<a href="http://www.npr.org/">National Public Radio</a>
and <a href="gopher://info.umd.edu:925/">CNN.</a></ul>

<p>
<p>
