<p><hr><p>
<a name="tv">
<center><h2><font size=+3>I</font>NSIDE <font size=+3>D.C.</font></h2></center>
<p><hr width=30% size=2><p>
<center><font size=+2><b><i>FRC Goes to the Wire</i></b></font><br>
by Gary L. Bauer</center>
<p>
<font size=+3>R</font>ecently I ran into Republican Sen. Arlen Specter of 
Pennsylvania after a lunch in the Senate Dining Room in the U.S. Capitol. 
Many times the senator and I have taken debater's chairs opposite each 
other, even discussing some of our differences on national television.
<p>
&quot;You're the only one who will debate with me about abortion,&quot;
he told me and joked that we should take our &quot;act&quot; on the road.
It has been a privilege for me to talk about social issues on
behalf of the many people who support the Family Research Council. Every 
day, reporters from organizations such as <i>The New York Times</i>, 
<i>The Washington Post</i> and the nightly news shows call us
at FRC for our -- and what we hope is your -- perspective.  But usually 
an hour-long conversation with a reporter becomes a 10-second soundbite 
on the network news or less than an inch of copy at the bottom of a 
two-column story.
<p>
Not any longer.  Our dream of providing a pro-family voice is
much bigger than merely building a conservative &quot;speed bump&quot; 
in a vast terrain of liberal reporting. That is why we are about to
premiere our own television show.  Our vision is to help a national
audience understand not only what we believe but why we support the kind 
of pro-family reforms that we advocate daily in Washington. Our aim is 
to make a connection with even more of those millions of Americans
who go to work every morning worrying about the kind of world
their children are inheriting.
<p>
Beginning Wednesday, Nov. 1, &quot;Straight Talk from the Family
Research Council&quot; will air at 8 p.m. on the new cable network 
National Empowerment Television (NET). We will be coming to
you on a weekly basis thereafter.
<p>
The show includes such segments as &quot;Behind the Headlines,&quot;
an insider's look at what is happening to the family in Washington, 
and &quot;Homefront News,&quot; which will highlight what FRC
has been doing to bolster the family.  The majority of our show,
however, will be fast-paced discussions of the answers pro-family 
advocates offer to the tough social questions we face today.
<p>
We believe &quot;Straight Talk&quot; has the potential to break
out of the 10-second soundbite box that conservatives usually occupy 
on television.  Family issues deserve in-depth treatment.  Most of
all, we hope to provide you with the kind of informative discussion
that will help you in your own understanding of the state of the 
family today -- in politics, in society, and beyond.
<p>
This is an exciting new venture for FRC.  NET now reaches into
more than 11 million homes and is growing daily. &quot;Straight Talk&quot; 
is an important addition to the network's menu.  We invite you to
watch and share your comments with us as the show unfolds.
<p>
Here's thanking you in advance for the kind of support that has
made &quot;Straight Talk&quot; possible.
<p><hr width=45% size=2><p>
<center><i><font size=+2>AN EXCITING NEW<br>
VENTURE FOR FRC</font></i></center>
<p><hr width=45% size=2><p>
<center><h3>To learn whether your cable company carries NET:</h3></center>
<p>
Check local listings or call your cable carrier.  If you have
a satellite dish, NET can be reached on Galaxy 7, Transponder 20. 
To obtain a listing of cities where the network currently operates, 
or a postcard you can mail to your local cable operator requesting
the network, call 1-800-225-4008.
<p><hr><p>
<a name="lobby">
<center><h2><font size=+3>S</font>PECIAL <font size=+3>R</font>EPORT:</h2>
<h4>Lobbying Reform</h4></center>
<p><hr width=30% size=2><p>
For years, political advocacy groups have taken advantage of the
public purse to finance their agenda.  Groups like Planned Parenthood 
receive millions of federal dollars each year, even as 
they engage in high-powered lobbying and political advocacy.
<p>
During its consideration of a multi-billion dollar appropriations
bill earlier this year, the House of Representatives adopted an 
amendment to prohibit recipients of federal grants from spending any
grant funds on political advocacy.  The amendment, sponsored by
Rep. Ernest Istook (R-Okla.), also proposed strict limits on the 
amount of political advocacy a grantee could engage in with
&quot;non-grant&quot; funds.  Rep. David McIntosh (R-Ind.) chairs
a House subcommittee that has held hearings and urged limits on such 
advocacy.
<p>
A coalition of liberal organizations has mounted a fierce campaign
to scuttle lobbying reform. This campaign has stalled the Treasury-Postal 
appropriations bill for several weeks.  The Clinton
Administration is threatening a veto if the Istook-McIntosh provision
is included in the final bill. The issue is likely to come to a head in 
mid-November.
<p>
<b>Action Item:</b> Call your congressman and senators today.  Tell
them it is time for genuine reform of the congressional spending process. 
A vital first step is to end &quot;welfare&quot; for lobbyists. 
<p><hr><p>
<a name="horizon">
<center><h2><font size=+3>O</font>N THE <font size=+3>H</font>ORIZON</h2></center>
<p>
To help politicians summon the courage to scale back the role
of government in American life, FRC will host a one-day symposium 
on Dec. 13 in Washington, D.C. The topic will be government's 
contribution to cultural decay.  The conference will launch a new 
initiative to cultivate charitable alternatives to the welfare state. 
Under the leadership of Forest Thigpen, the Mississippi Family Council 
recently hosted a similar event, entitled &quot;Leading People Out of 
Poverty,&quot; that attracted some of the nation's leading authorities 
on reform. To order tapes, contact the Mississippi Family Council at 
(601) 969-1200.
