<html>
<title>Where Teachers Send Their Own Children To School -- Heritage</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg"><center>

<h3><i>WHERE TEACHERS SEND THEIR OWN CHILDREN TO SCHOOL</i></h3>
By Denis Doyle and James Hirni<br>
<a href="/heritage/">The Heritage Foundation</a><br>
Business/Education Insider No. 42<br>
October-November 1995<br>
<hr width=50%></center>
<p>
<blockquote>"If teachers and their organizations reject the institutions they are teaching in and feel free to choose a private alternative, on what basis should other parents, particularly the poor and dispossessed, be denied this option?"</blockquote><p>
  This pointed question was posed by Denis Doyle, Heritage Foundation Senior Fellow in Educational Policy, during a recent lecture in Washington on his latest study, which shows where public school teachers send their children to school.
<p>
Drawing on 1990 Census data, Doyle finds that, taken together, public and private school teachers nationwide are only slightly more likely than the general public to choose private schools (17.1 percent to 13.1 percent). But in America's most troubled cities, the pattern is quite different:  Public school teachers are two to three times more likely than the general public to use private schools. For example, in Washington, D.C., 25.7 percent of the children of the city's public school teachers who make less than $35,000 attend private school. This is more than double the national average; among public school teachers nationwide, 11.9 percent enroll some or all of their children in private school. The pattern continues in cities like Boston (24.4 percent), New York (21.4 percent), Miami (35.4 percent), and Los Angeles (18.9 percent). As Doyle observes, "in America's cities, where the schools are arguably the worst, a large number of teachers abandon the institutions in which they work and enroll their offspring in private schools."
<p>
Doyle's study also analyzes the relationship between race and a public school teacher's use of private schools. Doyle finds that, nationally, black public school teachers use private schools more than white public school teachers (12.9 percent to 11.9 percent), and Hispanic public school teachers use private schools more than non-Hispanic public school teachers (16.5 percent to 11.9 percent). Meanwhile, white parents are somewhat more likely than nonwhite parents to send their children to private school. In the United States as a whole, 13.1 percent of all parents, 14.2 percent of white parents, 8.1 percent of black parents, and 10.8 percent of parents of other races send their children to private schools. Some 13.4 percent of Hispanic parents send their children to private school, while 10.1 percent of all non-Hispanic parents do so.
<p>
Doyle notes that black public school teachers are almost as likely as the public at large to use private schools (12.9 percent compared with 13.1 percent). He concludes that "black teachers who can afford a choice exercise it:  they are 50 percent more likely than black parents in general to enroll their children in private school. This might explain the high support for publicly funded school choice programs among minorities--they are often in the worst school districts and are more inclined to put their children in private schools when they can afford it."
<P>
Doyle says that "teachers--public and private, white and black, Hispanic and non-Hispanic, low income, middle income, and high income--know how to address the nation's education crisis:  they vote with their feet and their pocket books. They choose private schools for their children when they think it serves their interests best."
<p>
"When public-school teachers choose private schools," says Doyle, "the truth is self-evident:  although they work in public schools they choose private schools for their own children because they believe the latter are better. They are connoisseurs."
<p>
<i>To order a copy of Denis Doyle's study "Where the Connoisseurs Send Their Children to School," call the Center for Education Reform at (202)822-9000, or write the Center at 1001 Connecticut Avenue, N.W., Suite 920, Washington, D.C. 20036.</i>
<p>
<b>WISCONSIN PRIVATE PHILANTHROPISTS SUPPORT CHOICE</b>
<p>
In response to an August 25 Wisconsin State Supreme Court injunction halting the expansion of the Milwaukee Parental Choice Program (MPCP) to include religious, independent, and newly founded schools, private citizens in Wisconsin donated more than $1.8 million as of September 22 to help give the children of Milwaukee the right to stay in the schools of their choice. The campaign was led by Partners Advancing Values in Education (PAVE), Milwaukee's privately funded scholarship program. Of the $1.8 million raised for the fund, $1 million came from the Bradley Foundation in Milwaukee and $125,000 was donated by the Metropolitan Milwaukee Association of Commerce.
<p>
The Court's August 25 ruling put a stop to the Milwaukee choice expansion program and left more than 2,300 children stranded after they had already signed up for classes in the religious schools of their choice. The state and local teachers' unions, along with the ACLU, backed the lawsuit which resulted in the temporary injunction.
<p>
The case is to be heard soon by the Wisconsin State Supreme Court, and a decision is expected before the end of the year. According to the Landmark Legal Foundation of Kansas City, Missouri, which is providing legal support for the children, "the Milwaukee school choice litigation will ultimately result in a major U.S. Supreme Court decision allowing school choice programs that include religious programs."
<p>
<i>Copies of the July 1995 Wisconsin statutes enabling the expansion of Milwaukee's Parental Choice Program to include religious schools and the affidavits filed recently in the Wisconsin Supreme Court are available from the Blum Center for Parental Freedom in Education, Marquette University, PO Box 1881, Milwaukee, Wisconsin 53201-1881.</i>
<p>
<b>HIGH MARKS FOR WISCONSIN SCHOLARSHIP PROGRAM</b>
<p>
In a related development, Family Service America (FSA), the largest international non-profit association dedicated to strengthening family life through education and research, has completed its independent, third-year evaluation of the Partners Advancing Values in Education scholarship program in Milwaukee.
<p>
PAVE is the nation's largest privately funded school choice program. Its design closely resembles Wisconsin Governor Tommy Thompson's recently expanded Milwaukee Parental Choice Program, which is publicly funded. In the 1994 school year, PAVE provided scholarships to 2,654 low-income students who attended 84 elementary and 13 secondary private or parochial schools in Milwaukee.
<p>
FSA's first-year evaluation of the program reported high levels of parent satisfaction (96 percent) and involvement (97 percent) among the 960 (63 percent) families who completed a survey. The second-year evaluation investigated seventh graders' academic achievement and reported that PAVE students scored higher in reading and math than did representative samples from Milwaukee public schools.
<p>
The purpose of the third-year evaluation was to determine whether parental satisfaction and involvement were consistent over the three years of PAVE's scholarship program for low-income families in Milwaukee.
<p>
<b>Findings of the third-year evaluation:</b>
<p>
"The overwhelming majority of parents were satisfied with the performance of the schools."  The responses indicated the following levels of satisfaction:<p>
<ul>
<li><b>96 percent</b> with the teacher's performance,
<li><b>94 percent</b> with the principal's performance,
<li><b>92 percent</b> with the discipline of the school,
<li><b>97 percent</b> with the program of instruction,
<li><b>96 percent</b> with textbooks,
<li><b>96 percent</b> with amount child learned,
<li><b>97 percent</b> with opportunities for parental involvement, and 
<li><b>97 percent</b> with school location.
</ul><P>
Some 92 percent of respondents rated their school "A" or "B."  Almost twice as many parents in each category were "very satisfied" rather than "satisfied."  And according to the study, parents became significantly involved in the schools of their choice:  96 percent attended parent-teacher conferences.
<p>
<i>Copies of the third annual evaluation of PAVE's Scholarship Program are available from Family Service America, (414)342-1505, 1434 West State Street, Milwaukee, Wisconsin 53233.</i>
<p>
<b>WASHINGTON UPDATE</b>
<p>
<b>AmeriCorps</b>
<p>
Backed by an unfavorable report from the General Accounting Office (GAO), the nonpartisan investigative arm of the national legislature, Congress is trying to end what critics call one of the federal government's largest boondoggles:  AmeriCorps, President Clinton's national service program. The House took the first step by voting to end funding for this high-priced program. The Senate, in  a 52 to 47 vote, followed suit on September 26. If enacted as part of the budget, this change would save the American taxpayers $575 million in FY 1996.
<p>
While the Clinton Administration and its supporters hail AmeriCorps as an innovative effort to expand educational opportunity through volunteerism, opponents say it has evolved into a big-government, pork-barrel project.
<p>
The August GAO report found that the new Clinton program cost $26,654 per participant to run, or more than 40 percent higher than the Administration's most recent estimates. Some 93 percent of the funding for the program comes out of taxpayers' pockets.
<p>
Senator Charles Grassley (R-IA) argues that in an era of budget deficits, the Administration was asking the American taxpayer to fund bureaucracies and paperwork while forcing the Congress to look elsewhere for cuts. Grassley also claims that the program does little to help American families pay for college, destroys the spirit of volunteerism, and removes participants from the local communities where they are needed most. Indications that AmeriCorps improperly funds political activities sealed the program's fate in the Senate's debate.
<p>
For more on Americorps, read  <a href="/heritage/library/categories/education/ib212.html">Americorps: A $575 Million Boondoggle</a> by James F. Hirni.<p>

<b>Direct Lending</b>
<p>
Congress is debating the future of President Clinton's direct lending program for student loans.
<p>
While the Clinton Administration has portrayed its direct lending program for college students as essential to the educational future of young Americans, the evidence suggests otherwise. The direct government lending program appears to be bad for taxpayers, bad for students, and bad for schools. 
<p>
The Senate has recommended an appropriation of $378 million for FY 1996. While this is $94.4 million more than the 1995 amount, it is $172 million less than the Administration's request. This has the effect of capping the program at 20 percent. The House has voted to zero out the program.
<P>
<b>Question of Cost.</b> Much of the congressional debate over direct loans turns on the crucial question of cost:  Replacing guaranteed loans with direct lending is supposed to save taxpayers billions of dollars. When the direct loan program was enacted in 1993, the Congressional Budget Office (CBO) initially estimated it could save $4.3 billion over five years. But this estimate ignored the long-term costs. The FY 1996 budget resolution amends the Credit Reform Act to account for the complicated long-term administrative costs of the direct loan program. 
<p>
A revised CBO report, released in July and based on changes in official budget scoring, projects that a fully implemented direct loan program would save only $115 million over the next seven years. Indeed, according to the CBO, eliminating the direct loan program entirely while maintaining a guaranteed loan program would save $1.5 billion in budget outlays over the next seven years. According to Representative Bill Goodling (R-PA), the guaranteed loan program is "one of the most successful" public-private sector partnerships.
<p>
The vast bulk of capital for student loans today is provided through private institutions. But under the Clinton plan, the federal government would borrow the money needed to provide capital for the loans. This would require the federal government to borrow an additional $20 billion-$25 billion each year. According to Representative Ernest Istook (R-OK), a complete shift to direct loans could add up to $348 billion to the national debt by the year 2014.
<p>
<b>Army of New Employees.</b> The U.S. Department of Education is expanding to handle the new program. The agency is hiring 600 new employees to administer the Clinton program and anticipates needing another 20,000 contract employees by the time the program is fully operational -- if Congress changes its mind and funds the program.
<p>
There are other worries about the direct lending program. Currently, some 75 percent of all available college financial aid comes from the federal government. If the federal government takes complete control of the loan program, colleges and universities in effect will become dependent on a single lender to support their students. The Department's power to control loan revenue, along with its expanded regulatory authority and enforcement power, will give the government vast influence over post-secondary education. Such financial power could provide the federal government an opportunity to influence or force curriculum changes, or to mandate such things as politically correct "diversity standards."
<p>
Today's guaranteed loan program is by no means perfect. Taxpayers still bear all the risk. But there have been several recent improvements in the program. For example, the loan application process has become simpler in recent years. The default rate also has been cut significantly.
<p>
There is little support for a government takeover of the guaranteed lending program. According to a nationwide poll of 1,000 respondents, 72 percent of Americans believe student loans should continue to be offered through private financial institutions, not the federal government. Congress would better serve both the students and the universities of America by eliminating the direct lending program and allowing the more economical and guaranteed lending program to provide the money to students.
<p>
For more on direct lending, read <a href="/heritage/library/categories/education/ib215.html">Time to End Costly Direct Student Loans</a> by Matthew Spalding.<p>
<CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER></body></html>
  
