<html>
<head><title>  Volunteerism Testimony -- PFF</title>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/pff/notebook.gif" LINK="#8C1717" VLINK="#545454"
 ALINK="#FF0000"> <ul><blockquote><a href="/pff"><img src="/pff/pffdoc.gif" align="right"border="0"></a>
<h2>AmeriCorps</h2>
<b>Testimony by Arianna Huffington <br>
To<br> The Subcommittee On Oversight And Investigations<p>
</b><p>
OCTOBER 17, 1995<P>
Mr. Chairman, I would like to thank you and the members of the subcommittee for inviting me to testify today.  I wish to speak about the difference between true volunteerism and paid "volunteerism," between the effective compassion that can come only from individuals, and the compulsory compassion of the bureaucratic welfare state.  I think that this is an important distinction to make, particularly here in Washington.  After all, only in Washington could you find someone who could miss the irony of paying someone for so-called "volunteer" work.  But I imagine you've heard a lot about that today.
<P>
I also wish to speak about the work we are doing at the Center for Effective Compassion that I have co-founded with Professor Marvin Olasky, and of the work that hundreds of  thousands of Americans are doing around the country everyday to help those most in need.   It is my unequivocal conclusion that Americorps, both as a reality and as a symbol, is hurting the work that has to be done if we are to solve the major social problems facing us.  It's hurting in three fundamental ways:
<P><OL>
<LI>It contradicts the basic religious and philosophical teachings about human nature, according to which human beings have an instinctive propensity to reach out and  help others.  This instinct -- which, in my latest book, I call the fourth instinct -- is competing with other, more self-interested instincts, but as a culture we need to do everything we can to strengthen the instinct that makes us part of a healthy community.  Americorps, by paying people to "volunteer" -- by paying them to do what should be done naturally as part of our learning to live and care for each other in society -- undermines that most important instinct in human beings.  
<LI>Americorps, in its small but significant way, like Great Society programs, in their all-pervasive way, cheats people out of the character-building rewards of giving.  We build up our moral muscle by exercising it.  We become virtuous by the practice of virtue, responsible by the practice of responsibility, generous by the practice of generosity, and compassionate by the practice of compassion.  And all these traits are being practiced because that's how we become fully human, not because we are being paid to practice them. 
<LI>The third, and most immediate, way Americorps undermines the practice of true, effective compassion is by standing in sharp contrast to the hard, unpaid, true volunteer work being done everyday in the trenches around America. What hundreds of thousands of people are doing everyday, Mr. Chairman, is rolling up their sleeves and actually helping to feed, to clothe, and to turn lives around. There was a very moving documentary on PBS last week about little-known, community-based groups working hard at tackling social problems in Anacostia.  How many of these groups are using Americorps volunteers?  Mr. Chairman, if these people were depending on  paid "volunteers" to keep going, they would have closed down long ago.</ol>
<P>Helping those in need is a moral imperative.  It is our responsibility -- our obligation -- and in a completely different realm from getting loans to go to school or money to live on.  These are all important necessities, but when we mix the two together, and, most important, when the mixing is done by the government at taxpayers' expense, something very important is lost -- both for the building of individual character and for the building of healthy communities. 
<P>The people I most admire in this world are volunteering their time everyday without the benefit of any fancy, bureaucratically-run programs.  Not too far from the Capitol, Mr. Chairman, there is Hannah Hawkins, a feisty, no-nonsense lady who runs an after-school program in Anacostia called Children of Mine.  Hannah serves hot meals to kids.  But she gives them much more than that.  She gives them the love and attention that many of them have never received at home.  She also gives them an important gift that government would never give -- Bible lessons, which teach them the difference between right and wrong, and which bring hope and meaning to their lives.  
<P>Also not too far from here are Marsh Ward and Julia Lightfoot, who run 
Clean and Sober Streets,  a safe harbor for drug and alcohol addicts who are trying to put their lives back together.  They give addicts the sort of attention and caring that they have not received before, particularly from government-run institutions
<P>In Denver, there is  Bob Cote, who runs a program called Step 13 in which he tries to help addicts turn their lives around.  Bob, a former addict himself, refers to the government-run programs as "suicide on the installment plan."  Bob's program houses 100 men a night; they are allowed to stay as long as they need to -- as long as they follow the rules, which include doing some kind of work each day as well as staying sober.  Bob's operation costs $300,000 a year, with no help from the government.  Bob estimates that if he were to do what he does now but with government money, it would cost more than $2 million because of all the absurd rules and regulations.  And that doesn't even count for having to pay for volunteers.
<P>In San Antonio, there is the Rev. Freddy Garcia, who runs a program called Victory Outreach, a combination church and halfway house for recovering addicts.  Rev. Garcia's success rate in getting people cleaned up and back on their feet is more than 60 percent.  Recently, the Texas Drug and Alcohol Commission asked Rev. Garcia to stop referring to his work as "drug rehabilitation" because he wasn't conforming with their regulations.
<P>And I could go on and on, Mr. Chairman. You probably haven't seen or heard of any of these people.  And  there's a simple explanation for this, Mr. Chairman: they aren't walking the corridors of Congress asking for government funds to sustain their programs.  And they most certainly do not believe that the best way to help the poor is to convince the government to help them.  Americorps is an affront to the people I mentioned and it is also a hindrance to the work Marvin Olasky and I are doing at the Center for Effective Compassion.  Our aim is nothing less than the transformation of America's efforts to aid those in need, from a bureaucratic, government-centered approach to a community-oriented, people-centered approach. 
<P>We have found plenty of inspiration for our work in American history, going back to the Pilgrims.  When the Pilgrims needed help to survive their first winter at Plymouth Colony, the Indians didn't simply give them a hand-out -- they gave them a hand-up.  Squanto taught them how to plant their corn successfully in New England's difficult soil.
<P>Squanto's act of effective compassion is the origin of Thanksgiving.  The hand-up made a huge difference.  The Indians didn't just run a soup kitchen or donate food to their neighbors; but too often that is what we do today.  The hand-out stems hunger for a while -- the hand-up banishes it forever. 
<P>I do not mean to diminish the effort or goodwill of Americans who will volunteer their time on food lines or organize food drives this Thanksgiving.  They are making a difference and brightening the holiday for many.  But what is needed is their involvement in making a lasting difference, as Squanto did with the Pilgrims.  
<P>Through a national campaign we are launching during Thanksgiving week, we hope to challenge some of our long-held assumptions regarding giving. Our message is simple: For compassion to be effective, it must be personal, challenging, and spiritual.  It does not involve government, and it most certainly does not involve payment for what is a natural duty and responsibility that we need to nurture from the time our children are very young.  I don't want my daughters when they are teenagers to say to me: "Why should I volunteer for free, Mom?  Dick and Jane are getting paid for it!"   



<p><center></center><P><P>
</blockquote></ul><p><br><center><a href="/pff/footer.map"><img src="/pff/footer.gif" border="0" ISMAP></a></center></BODY>
</html>
