<DOCHDR>
http://www.atr.org:80/townhall/FRC/perspective/pv95i1dr.html 204.71.237.87 19970209203343 text/html 6618
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 20:34:29 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 14-Mar-96 15:11:57 GMT
Content-length: 6433
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<title>DO WE NEED A DRUG CZAR?</title>
<body>
<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">
<h2>DO WE NEED A DRUG CZAR?</h2>
<hr size=3 width=50%><p>
<i>by</i>
<p>
<i>Robert L. Maginnis</i></center>
<p>
A Senate committee voted to abolish the White House drug czar
and move its function to the Treasury Department saving $10 million
next year.  Senator Richard Shelby (R-AL) explained, &quot;If
this administration will not facilitate and prosecute the drug
war, then Congress is forced to do it for them.&quot;  Clinton
promises to veto the bill if the final version eliminates the
Office of National Drug Control Policy.
<P>
Shelby says the administration is sending &quot;a mixed message
to America's youth -- a message that doing drugs is not a crime.
 I object to the administration's handling of this issue, its
lack of commitment to enforcement.&quot;   He blames drug czar
Lee Brown for &quot;lack of visibility&quot; in fighting illegal
drug use and trafficking.
<P>
Senator Shelby is correct about &quot;a mixed message.&quot; 
The Clinton administration has overseen an all-out retreat in
the drug war.
<P>
At a hearing before a House committee earlier this year, former
First Lady Nancy Reagan said, &quot;Why is it we no longer hear
the drumbeat of condemnation against drugs coming from our leaders
and our culture?&quot;  Former drug czar William Bennett echoed
Reagan's point, there is &quot;no viable effort by the Clinton
Administration to prevent the complete disintegration of foreign
supply control.&quot;  And former DEA director Robert Bonner stated,
&quot;I believe that there has been a near total absence of presidential
leadership by President Clinton in the fight to turn back illegal
drug use in this country.&quot;
<P>
At the same hearing Lee Brown began his testimony with an unusual
and telling aside.  He told the committee, &quot;I am extremely
disappointed by the way that you have structured this hearing.
 You have placed me on the third panel to testify, following the
appointees of the last administration.  This is contrary to established
precedent in the House for scheduling of administration witnesses
regardless of which party sits in the White House.&quot;
<P>
The administration's anti-drug record possibly explains the House's
witness sequence and the low esteem accorded Dr. Brown.  Even
Democratic Congressmen piled on the drug czar.  Rep. Charles Rangel
(D-NY) said, &quot;I've been in Congress for over two decades,
and I have never, never, never seen a 
president who cares less about this issue.&quot;  Rep. John Conyers
(D-MI) told Lee Brown during the drug czar's confirmation hearings,
&quot;Either the president is with you, or he has just given you
a chair at the cabinet level...If it is the latter, you are getting
ready to be the biggest fall guy in the Clinton Administration.&quot;
<P>
Probably the latter is closer to the truth.  The question remains,
should Congress discard the drug czar's post because Clinton isn't
committed to the war?  After all, when the ONDCP was established
by Congress in 1988, it was authorized to develop and coordinate
the policies, goals, and objectives for the drug fight.  What's
lacking in this administration is vision and leadership.  Snuffing
out an issue coordinator at the cabinet level is not the right
decision.
<P>
Senator Shelby would transfer the drug czar's responsibilities
to the Treasury Department.  But placing drug policy under Treasury
might further taint drug enforcement given the problems now linked
with the ATF.   Other anti-drug efforts like prevention and treatment
would likely suffer.
<P>
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin supports the existing drug office.
 &quot;ONDCP is critical,&quot; says Rubin, &quot;because it is
a neutral agency coordinating all the 50 agencies with anti-drug
roles.&quot;  Even Attorney General Janet Reno sees a &quot;need
to continue a strong and coordinated effort&quot; played by the
drug czar.  
<P>
Brown defends his post:  &quot;The deletion of funding for the
ONDCP will undercut the President's ability to fight drugs and
drug-related crime, which recent polls confirm are America's greatest
fear.&quot;  He points out that 77 million Americans report some
history of using illicit drugs.
<P>
Brown shouldn't be faulted for his boss's apparent indifference
to the drug problem.  One of the czar's primary duties is to advise
the president.  But if his advice is ignored and Clinton fails
to personally support the drug war, it will languish.
<P>
Brown said that &quot;Shutting off the relatively small $9.9 million
for our office will do irreparable damage to the nation's ability
to have a coordinated anti-drug strategy.&quot;  Of course he's
right.  Treasury cannot effectively coordinate government-wide
anti-drug efforts.  Eliminating Brown's job because his boss doesn't
care is wrong.
<P>
This nation needs a coordinated anti-drug program and it begins
with a committed president.  The drug czar is an important player,
but he can't take the lead alone.  
<P>
With abuse rates rising and the culture glamorizing illicit drugs,
now is not the time to abandon what the czar's office represents:
a coordinated anti-drug commitment.
<P>
-- 8/21/95
<p>
<center>***</center>
<p>
<I>Robert Maginnis is a policy analyst with the Family Research
Council, a Washington, D.C. -based research and advocacy organization.
</I>

