<html><title>Press Release</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg"><center><h2>News Release</h2></center>
<hr> 

Contact: Ann Klucsarits 
(202)608-6016
<hr>
<h3>   
<center>TOWN HALL Hosts Bob Dornan Conference On-Line<br>
CompuServe reserves Convention Center for event</center>
</h3>
<p>
WASHINGTON, DC, September 18, 1995 -- Town Hall announced today that it will be hosting an on-line conference featuring California Republican Congressman and presidential hopeful, Robert "B-1 Bob" Dornan. The conference will be held in the CompuServe convention center on Friday, September 22, 1995 from 9:00 p.m. - 11:00 p.m. (EST).  Any CompuServe member can participate by typing CONVENTION at the GO prompt.
<P>
Rep. Dornan will discuss his race for the 1996 GOP presidential nomination and why he believes it so important that the views he holds be openly and strongly discussed in the public arena. These views include tax relief for American families, a Balanced Budget Amendment, the protection of innocent, pre-born children, school choice and school prayer, a strong national defense and immigration reform.
<P>
Not surprisingly, Dornan's views are often attacked by the national
media as "extremist" or "far right." But Dornan, an Irish-Catholic who
scored a perfect 1994 rating from the American Conservative Union
(ACU), has confounded critics by consistently winning in a majority
Democrat district without ever backing away from his core conservative
beliefs. 
<P>
This is Rep. Dornan's second on-line conference through Town Hall. The overwhelming popularity of his first conference required Town Hall to utilize the CompuServe's larger convention hall that has a capacity for over 1,000 on-line users.
<P>
Dornan represents California's 46th Congressional District -- a community that includes most of the Orange County cities of Anaheim, Santa Ana and Garden Grove. Rep. Dornan is Ranking Republican Member of the House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence and Chairman of the Subcommittee on Tactical and Technical Intelligence, Member of the House National Security Committee and Chairman of its Subcommittee on Personnel.
<P>
Town Hall, Inc., based in Washington, DC, is the nation's leading interactive computer network for conservatives.  A project of The Heritage Foundation and National Review magazine, Town Hall offers conservatives both an Internet site (http://www.townhall.com) and a private forum on CompuServe to share ideas, conduct research, and plan strategy.  CompuServe users can access the Town Hall forum by typing TOWNHALL at the GO prompt.  Other personal computer users can obtain a free 30-day trial to Town Hall by calling 800-441-4142.
<P>
